tool.summary:
This tool assigns a number of geomorphology classification attributes to the input seabed feature class. Based on the user choices from the drop-down lists and free text entries, the following attributes are added to describe the geomorphology of the selected feature(s) using the classification scheme of Nanson et al. (2023).

  1. PhysiogSetting: This is the physiography setting attribute which describes the physiography of the feature. The followings are the available choices: 'NA', 'abyssal plain', 'accretionary prism', 'axial high', 'axial valley', 'back-arc basin', 'continental rise ', 'continental shelf', 'continental slope', 'fore-arc basin', 'island arc', 'mid-ocean ridge ' and 'oceanic trench '.

  2. GeomorphSetting: This is the geomorphology setting or process attribute which describes the specific environments or processes the feature are formed. The followings are the available choices: 'NA', 'Unknown', 'Anthropogenic', 'Biogenic', 'Coastal', 'Current-induced', 'Fluid Flow', 'Fluvial', 'Glacial', 'Karst', 'Marine', 'Mass Movement' and 'Solid Earth'.

  3. Basic_Geom_Unit: This is the Basic Geomorphic Unit (BGU) attribute. BGU is the broadest geomorphic term. The choices of BGU are depended on the user selection of geomorphology setting or process.

  4. BGU_T: This is the BGU type (BGU_T) attribute. BGU_T is defined for commonly used sub-categories of BGU. The choices of BGU_T are depended on the user selection of BGU.

  5. BGU_sT: This is the BGU subtype attribute. BGU_sT provides more granular classification of BGU_T. The choices of BGU_sT are depended on the user selection of BGU_T.

  6. ProcessAttribute: This is the additional process attribute. This attribute is only available when user selects the Current-induced geomorphology setting or process. The followings are the available choices: 'erosional', 'accretionary/aggradational', 'unidirectional flow', 'bidirectional flow', 'interference', 'constrained flow', 'open flow', 'tidal current', 'turbidity current' and 'density current'.

  7. GeometricAttribute: This is the additional geometric attribute. This attribute is only available when user selects the Current-induced geomorphology setting or process. The followings are the available choices: '2D', '3D', 'primary', 'secondary', 'compound', 'longitudinal', 'transverse', 'oblique', 'straight crests', 'sinuous crests', 'linguoid crests', 'lunate crests' and 'crescent'.

  8. Grouping: This is the Group of units attribute which is the delineation of groups of smaller geomorphic units. There are two choices: 'field' and 'chain'.

  9. Age: This is the relative age attribute which indicates relative age of the feature. There are three choices: 'relict', 'palimpsest' and 'modern'.

  10. StratPosition: This is the stratigraphic position attribute which describes the stratigraphic position of the feature. There are three choices: 'surface', 'buried' and 'partially buried'.

  11. SeaLevel: This is the relative sea level attribute which indicates the relative sea level history of the feature in broad term. There are six choices according to Catuneanu et al. (2009): 'aggradational', 'forced regressive', 'normal regressive', 'lowstand normal regressive', 'highstand normal regressive' and 'transgressive'.

  12. Lithology: Lithology attribute describes the lithological characterisation of the sediment or rock samples collected for the feature. There are three choices: 'hard', 'soft sediment (siliciclastic or carbonate)' and 'consolidated sediment'.

  13. MeanGrainSize: This is the particle size characterisation attribute which quantifies the mean grain size distribution of the sediment sample collected for the feature. User must enter the value in either 'mm' or 'phi' unit.

  14. FolkTexture: This is the particle size characterisation attribute which assigns the sediment texture class for the feature according to the modified Folk classification (Folk, 1954). There are 15 choices: 'G', 'mG', 'msG', 'sG', 'gM', 'gmS', 'gS', '(g)M', '(g)sM', '(g)mS', '(g)S', 'M', 'sM', 'mS' and 'S'.

  15. GravelSandMudContents: This is the particle size characterisation attribute which quantifies the gravel, sand and mud contents (as percentages) of the sediment samples collected for the feature. User must enter their values in a range of 0-100.

  16. TerrainAttributes: Terrain attributes characterise the feature using derivatives derived from bathymetric data such as slope, orientation, curvature or rugosity etc. This attribute is a free text entry.

  17. ProcessClass: This is the marginal marine process classification attribute which describes the formative process ratios (wave, tide and fluvial) for the feature. The attribute uses the primary, secondary and tertiary ternary classification levels of Ainworth et al. (2011). The followings are the choices: 'Fluvial dominated', 'Wave dominated', 'Tide dominated', 'Fluvial dominated, wave influenced', 'Fluvial dominated, tide influenced', 'Tide dominated, fluvial influenced', 'Tide dominated, wave influenced', 'Wave dominated, tide influenced', 'Wave dominated, fluvial influenced', 'Fluvial dominated, wave influenced, tide affected', 'Fluvial dominated, tide influenced, wave affected', 'Tide dominated, fluvial influenced, wave affected', 'Tide dominated, wave influenced, fluvial affected', 'Wave dominated, tide influenced, fluvial affected', 'Wave dominated, fluvial influenced, tide affected', 'fluvial and wave influenced', 'tide and fluvial influenced', 'wave and tide influenced', 'fluvial, wave and tide influenced', 'Fluvial dominated, wave and tide influenced', 'Tide dominated, wave and fluvial influenced' and 'Wave dominated, tide and fluvial influenced'.

  18. AeolianInput: Aeolian input attribute indicates whether the feature has an element of aeolian origin or modification.

  19. Comments: The attribute records the free text comments from user.

  20. GeomorphAnalystName: This is the geomorphology analyst name attribute which records the name of the geomorphology analyst who undertakes the geomorphology interpretation.

  21. GeomorphAnalystOrganisation: This is the geomorphology analyst organisation attribute which records the organisation of the geomorphology analyst who undertakes the geomorphology interpretation.

Note that the mean grain size, the Folk texture and the gravel, sand and mud contents parameters are grouped under the Particle size characterisation category. The comments, the geomorphology analyst name and the geomorphology analyst organisation parameters are grouped under the Geomorphology analyst category.

Note that the reset parameter (under the Reset parameters category) is used to reset the existing parameter values to their default values.

Note that 'NA' indicates that classification at this level is not appropriate/applicable to the setting/process, or level of detail is out of scope and has not been attempted; while 'Unknown' indicates that there is insufficient data available to determine a geomorphology classification for a mapped morphology feature.

The definitions of the Physiography terms are available in this vocabulary link: https://pid.geoscience.gov.au/def/voc/ga/SeabedGeomorphologyPhysiography. The definitions of the Geomorphology terms (geomorphology setting and process, Basic Geomorphic Unit, and Basic Geomorphic Unit Type) are available in this vocabulary link: https://pid.geoscience.gov.au/def/voc/ga/SeabedGeomorphologySettings.

Ainsworth, R.B., Vakarelov, B.K., Nanson, R.A., 2011. Dynamic spatial and temporal prediction of changes in depositional processes on clastic shorelines: toward improved subsurface uncertainty reduction and management. AAPG bulletin 95, 267–297.

Catuneanu, O., Abreu, V., Bhattacharya, J.P., Blum, M.D., Dalrymple, R.W., Eriksson, P.G., Fielding, C.R., Fisher, W.L., Galloway, W.E., Gibling, M.R. and Giles, K.A., 2009. Towards the standardization of sequence stratigraphy. Earth-Science Reviews, 92(1-2), pp.1-33.

Folk, R., L., 1954. The distinction between grain size and mineral composition in sedimentary rock nomenclature. Journal of Geology 62, 344–359.

Nanson, R., Arosio, R., Gafeira, J., McNeil, M., Dove, D., Bjarnadóttir, L., Dolan, M.F.J., Guinan, J., Post, A., Webb, J. and S. Nichol. 2023. A two-part seabed geomorphology classification scheme. Part 2: Geomorphology classification framework and glossary. https://zenodo.org/record/7804019
